<article>
  <span class="badge badge-danger">XSS RISK</span>
  <h2>1. The XSS Risk</h2>

  <div class="csp-indicator csp-off">
    ● Trusted Types: OFF (no CSP on this page)
  </div>

  <p>
    <code>unsafeHTML()</code> renders a raw string directly as HTML. If that string
    comes from user input — even indirectly — it's an XSS sink.
  </p>

  <p>
    Click "Run Demo" below. The XSS payload <code>&lt;img src=x onerror="alert('XSS!')"&gt;</code>
    is passed directly to <code>unsafeHTML()</code>. Without sanitization, the
    <code>onerror</code> handler fires immediately.
  </p>

  <div class="code-block">
    <div class="code-block-label">demo-1.js — what you're running</div>
{% highlight "javascript" %}
import { html, render } from 'lit-html';
import { unsafeHTML } from 'lit-html/directives/unsafe-html.js';

const userInput = `<img src=x onerror="alert('XSS!')"> Hello!`;

render(
  html`<div>${unsafeHTML(userInput)}</div>`,
  document.querySelector('#result')
);
{% endhighlight %}
  </div>

  <div class="demo-area">
    <h3>Interactive Demo</h3>
    <button class="run-btn" id="run-btn">Run Demo</button>
    <div class="result-box" id="result">
      <em style="color:#999">Output will appear here after clicking "Run Demo".</em>
    </div>
  </div>

  <p style="margin-top:1.5rem">
    The alert fires because <code>unsafeHTML</code> sets <code>innerHTML</code>
    via a fake <code>TemplateStringsArray</code>, giving the browser no chance to
    intercept the injection.
  </p>

